I prefer implementing WebDriver extensions such as `WaitForElementToExist` to assist with explicit waits.

Here&#39;s some code to explicitly wait for an element to exist before clicking. I implement within a try / catch block so that I can handle any exceptions at the PageObject level, rather than break the entire test when an element is not found:

````
        public static bool WaitForElementToExist(this AndroidDriver&lt;AppiumWebElement&gt; driver, By by, int seconds = 30)
        {
            var wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(seconds));
            try
            {
                wait.Until(d =&gt; d.FindElements(by).Count &gt; 0);
                return true;
            }
            catch (Exception e)
            {
                return false;
            }
        }
````

With this method, you can explicitly wait for an element to exist before clicking it:

```` 
     driver.WaitForElementToExist(by);
     driver.FindElement(by).Click();
````

This method returns `false` when the element we are waiting for does not exist. This allows for additional exception handling in the Test class / Page Object level:

````
    bool doesElementExist = driver.WaitForElementToExist(by);
    if (!doesElementExist)
    {
        // refresh the page or handle the case where element does not exist
    }

    else
    {
        driver.FindElement(by).Click();
    }
````
Note that when implementing this, you should NOT set an implicit wait on your driver, otherwise you will end up duplicating waits.

